Question: How to access value "c"? Answer should be like obj[key or index 1][key or index 2][key or index 3]...
Answer: You can access the value "c" by using the following code:


```python
obj = {
    "id": "e",
    "Z": "c",
    "subs": [
        {
            "id": "f",
            "Y": "b",
            "subs": [
                {
                    "id": "g",
                    "X": "a",
                    "subs": []
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

# Access value "c" from the "Z" key in the outer-most object
value = obj["Z"]
print(value)  # Output: c
```
In this case, you can access the value "c" by using the key "Z" in the outer-most object. You can access nested objects and arrays by using their keys or indices. In this case, you can access the value "c" from the nested object "subs" of the object "obj".

Remember that in Python, unlike some other programming languages, it is not necessary to specify an index for accessing an array or object. You can simply use its key or name to access it.
